    <content type="html"><![CDATA[
        <p>I talked to a developer last week who has been teaching kids to code in an after school program. </p>
<p>His teaching secret? </p>
<p>Teach using this format: <strong>Motivate &gt; Set a Goal &gt; Work through the problem together.</strong></p>
<h2>Keep It Simple &amp; Move Fast</h2>
<p>I think it's a helpful starting place when the big, scary idea of &quot;CODING&quot; seems intimidating.</p>
<p>Start by understanding <strong>what</strong> you want to change in the world and <strong>why.</strong> (Motivation!) </p>
<p>Set a concrete goal of a small feature / slice of an application that would solve a problem ‚Äî even if it's small and silly. (That's a goal!) </p>
<p>Then chip off a small piece of your day to work toward your achievable goal as quickly as possible. Rinse &amp; repeat.</p>
<p>It's not a bulletproof way to learn code. (I mean... Is there a &quot;right&quot; way to learn?) But, I think it's a useful framework for biting off a quick win when someone's just dipping their toes in the water.</p>    ]]></content>
