Starting my dream job working at an OKC software startup
Meeting......</summary>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[
        <p><img src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1600/0*BiS6-dB2-94d4VI6" alt="" /></p>
<p>Fact: OKC‚Äôs Thunderplains Conference has altered the trajectory of my career in a massively positive way.</p>
<p>If you told me a year ago before my first time attending that it would lead to:</p>
<ol>
<li>Starting my dream job working at an OKC software startup</li>
<li>Meeting invaluable friends, mentors, and impressive makers through the local Techlahoma community</li>
<li>Amplifying my excitement for development, which would lead to massive personal growth (and happiness)</li>
</ol>
<p>I would‚Äôve had no idea. But I hope sharing my experience will encourage at least one person on the fence about jumping into local tech events to see what‚Äôs possible.</p>
<iframe width="560" height="315" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/ZlUtROlD_K0" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>
<h2>1. I Learned to Always Say ‚ÄúYes‚Äù to Public Speaking (Even When It‚Äôs Scary)</h2>
<iframe src="https://giphy.com/embed/jndc0TQq9fvK8" width="480" height="317" frameborder="0" class="giphy-embed" allowfullscreen></iframe>
<p>Last year was the first time I really tried my hand at a ‚ÄúLightning Talk‚Äù‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääa quick, 5-minute presentation. Here‚Äôs the thing: I almost never actually feel like signing-up at the time, but I‚Äôm always glad when I do.</p>
<p>It‚Äôs easy to sit down, stay quiet, and feel safe. Stepping out feels vulnerable.</p>
<p>But I‚Äôm ridiculously glad after following through at Thunderplains the past two years. My split-second decision last year to rattle through a short talk on ‚ÄúMarketing Your Side Project on a Shoestring Budget‚Äù sparked an introduction with 3 Tailwind team members, which eventually lead to me joining the marketing team this May.</p>
<p>It just takes 5 minutes of bravery to open 5 months of new opportunities. Why not give it a shot?</p>
<p>Just focus on teaching one thing. Lightning talks don‚Äôt have to be crazy complicated to bring value. This year I simply broke down a few quick marketing and customer development lessons I‚Äôve gleaned from side projects and working alongside smart Tailwind folks.</p>
<p><strong>Remember:</strong> Your ideas might seem painfully obvious to you‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääbut this could be your audience‚Äòs first exposure to a game-changing idea.</p>
<iframe src="//www.slideshare.net/slideshow/embed_code/key/r0G3UZqZk3sJ83" width="595" height="485" frameborder="0" marginwidth="0" marginheight="0" scrolling="no" style="border:1px solid #CCC; border-width:1px; margin-bottom:5px; max-width: 100%;" allowfullscreen> </iframe>
<p>Here‚Äôs the LONG version of the presentation I gave. I whittled it down to about 14 slides to rip through the bare essentials in 4 minutes and 59 seconds.</p>
<h2>2. I Made Time and Space to Get Friendly with Oklahoma City‚Äôs Tech Community</h2>
<iframe src="https://giphy.com/embed/3ohhwgtTbYXLTssiek" width="480" height="271" frameborder="0" class="giphy-embed" allowfullscreen></iframe>
<p>Twitter‚Äôs a valuable platform for connecting with makers in tech. LinkedIn makes keeping in touch with professional connections frictionless. However‚Ä¶</p>
<p>Something special happens when you bring all your community‚Äôs like-minded makers together.</p>
<p>I‚Äôm constantly running into smart, talented, generous people I met for the first time at last year‚Äôs conference.</p>
<p>Striking up conversations with the developers around me opened my eyes to a simple truth: These are real people just like me. We all want to make cool stuff that matters.</p>
<p>Don‚Äôt underestimate how motivating this can be! I‚Äôm far more excited to jump into a local meetup now that I know a handful of people I can strike up an (only slightly awkward) conversation with.</p>
<h2>3. Excited Makers -&gt; Make You Excited</h2>
<iframe src="https://giphy.com/embed/yoJC2GnSClbPOkV0eA" width="480" height="401" frameborder="0" class="giphy-embed" allowfullscreen></iframe>
<p>Almost every week I chat with someone I‚Äôve met from a conference‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääand it always pumps me up.</p>
<p>There‚Äôs no way I‚Äôd be diving into marketing or software development if it weren‚Äôt for a crowd of talented, passionate people who:</p>
<ul>
<li>Introduced me to new frameworks, communities, strategies, blog posts, podcasts, and courses</li>
<li>Gave feedback on my podcasts, videos, and side project ideas</li>
<li>Keep me accountable to actually ship work‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääwhether it‚Äôs a blog post like this or a quick-and-dirty API.</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Key takeaway:</strong> Find people who get as excited as you do about creating impactful projects that make the world a better place. Surround yourself with them and stay in touch.</p>
<p>Last year I met Dale Spoonemore who shared his burning passion to create an app that could teach anyone to grow their own food in a backyard garden. Ambitious? Sure‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääbut he did it.</p>
<p>Last year, Seed to Spoon was more-or-less an idea in its infancy. This year he stood on stage at the closing keynote to share his riveting journey to 60,000 app downloads.</p>
<p><img src="https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1600/1*OBI4743TTqEkL6hd9g91Pw.png" alt="Dale Speaking" /></p>
<p>Dale is walking proof that you can code the change you want to see in the world‚Ää‚Äî‚Ääand that‚Äôs terrifically exciting.</p>
<h2>Want to work with me at Tailwind?</h2>
<p>Pssst‚Ä¶ Want to see what it‚Äôs actually like to work at a profitable startup growing +100% every year? Check it out and hit me up on <a href="https://twitter.com/matopher">Twitter</a> with honest questions: <a href="https://www.tailwindapp.com/careers">https://www.tailwindapp.com/careers</a></p>    ]]></content>
